        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          Bad atmosphere today. Even when we went a goal up, there was minimal excitement. It's something which has been labelled at us before and I understand the apprehension of some fans, but it's the first game of the season. I think the booing was a bit pointless since this team will likely only represent 45% of our first XI come September 1st. As for the game, we were much the better team in the first half and deserved to go in 1 up. Then Liverpool hit a real purple patch and we saw everything you'd expect to see from a Klopp team that are playing well. We battled well to get it back to 3-4 but in the end, we didn't have enough. The Liverpool fans should be more pessimistic than the Gooners imo. While we had players in the team who likely wont play from September barring injuries, Liverpool had pretty much their first choice XI out yet still looked vulnerable. We should be contenders with a CB, RW and F. Liverpool have made their signings and clearly wont be contenders.

        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          @WazzaFC- Wenger has been mediocre in recent memory, and I'm his biggest critic of all Arsenal fans on here, but he revolutionised football in this country and that is undeniable. From the professionalism to the quality of football played. Your beloved Utd played the best football in England before Wenger came but in comparison to the best in Europe, they were poor. Wenger's teams played football as good as anyone on the continent. In 1995, players in this country were still going to the pub & eating take-away food. Almost overnight he changed that at Arsenal and the rest of the prem followed. Remember, Ferguson was Mr 4-4-2 and played that system against everyone (including Bayern in the '99 CL final) but he always changed the formation to 4-3-3 against Wenger's Arsenal. Fergie was a better man-motivator & horses-for-courses tactician- which led to more success, but if you ask all the great managers who had the biggest impact on footballing identity of the prem, they would say Arsene.
